<script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-1.12.4.min.js" integrity="sha384-nvAa0+6Qg9clwYCGGPpDQLVpLNn0fRaROjHqs13t4Ggj3Ez50XnGQqc/r8MhnRDZ" crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<script src="~/Scripts/jquery.quiz-min.js"></script>
<script>
    $('#quiz').quiz({
        //resultsScreen: '#results-screen',
        //counter: false,
        //homeButton: '#custom-home',
        counterFormat: 'Question %current of %total',
        questions: [
            {
                'q': 'There are three types of bushfire warnings. Which is the most urgent??',
                'options': [
                    'Bushfire Advice',
                    'Bushfire Emergency',
                    'Bushfire Watch and Act'

                ],
                'correctIndex': 1,
                'correctResponse': 'Correct! Bushfire Emergency is the most urgent level of warning. An Emergency warning means you are in imminent danger and need to take action now. You will be impacted.',
                'incorrectResponse': 'Incorrect. Bushfire Emergency is the most urgent level of warning. A Watch and Act is the second level of warning. A Watch and Act warning means an emergency is heading towards you and conditions are changing and you need to take action now to protect yourself and your family.'
            },
            {
                'q': 'Make sure your bushfire survival kit is ready and you know of its location. What are some items you should include in your kit?',
                'options': [
                    'Battery-powered or wind-up radio',
                    'Waterproof torch',
                    'Toiletries including soap, hand wash gels, alcohol wipes, toilet paper, tissues, toothpaste and sanitary items',
                    'All of the above'
                ],
                'correctIndex': 3,
                'correctResponse': 'The correct answer is: All of the above! Good thinking. A battery-powered or wind-up radio means you can keep informed of the latest warnings on ABC Local Radio. It should be one part of your survival kit.',
                'incorrectResponse': 'Incorrect response. Correct answer is All of the above!'
            },
            {
                'q': 'If you decide to stay and defend your home, fire agencies recommend how many able-bodied, fit and determined adults as a minimum?',
                'options': [
                    'Two',
                    'Three',
                    'Five'

                ],
                'correctIndex': 1,
                'correctResponse': 'Correct! Fire agencies say defending your home requires at least two able-bodied, fit and determined adults. Both adults need to be sure theyre physically and mentally prepared to work in difficult conditions. But, homes in an area with a Code Red or Catastrophic fire danger rating are difficult to defend, even if well prepared.',
                'incorrectResponse': 'Incorrect, but an extra pair of hands can help. Fire agencies say defending your home requires at least two able-bodied, fit and determined adults. Both adults need to be sure they are physically and mentally prepared to work in difficult conditions. But, homes in an area with a Code Red or Catastrophic fire danger rating are difficult to defend, even if well prepared.'
            },
            {
                'q': 'How many litres of water are recommended to have on hand if you stay and defend your home?',
                'options': [
                    '1,000',
                    '5,000',
                    '10,000'
                ],
                'correctIndex': 2,
                'correctResponse': 'Correct. It is recommended that you have 10,000 litres of water for firefighting purposes as well as a firefighting pump and hoses. Other equipment needed includes a water sprayer, bucket, mop, shovel, torch and battery-powered radio. But remember, homes in an area with a Code Red or Catastrophic fire danger rating are difficult to defend, even if well prepared.',
                'incorrectResponse': 'Incorrect. It is recommended that you have 10,000 litres of water for firefighting purposes as well as a firefighting pump and hoses. Other equipment needed includes a water sprayer, bucket, mop, shovel, torch and battery-powered radio. But remember, homes in an area with a Code Red or Catastrophic fire danger rating are difficult to defend, even if well prepared.'
            },
            {
                'q': 'When should you work out your bushfire emergency plan',
                'options': [
                    'Around November as temperatures start to rise',
                    'Work out where you’re going on the day',
                    'Well in advance of bushfire season'
                ],
                'correctIndex': 2,
                'correctResponse': 'Correct! Well in advance. Dont wait and see. It is extremely dangerous to leave after there are signs of fire in your area. Come up with a plan to decide when to leave your home, where you will go and how you will get there. You should talk through your emergency plan with your family, as well as write it down. In an emergency you may not have time to plan.',
                'incorrectResponse': 'Incorrect. You should work out your bushfire plan well in advance. Dont wait and see. It is extremely dangerous to leave after there are signs of fire in your area. Come up with a plan to decide when to leave your home, where you will go and how you will get there. You should talk through your emergency plan with your family, as well as write it down. In an emergency you may not have time to plan.'
            },
            {
                'q': 'If someone is suffering from heatstroke due to hot conditions, what should you do?',
                'options': [
                    'Move them to a shaded area',
                    'Try to cool them down',
                    'Call 000',
                    'All of the above'
                ],
                'correctIndex': 3,
                'correctResponse': 'Correct! If someone is affected by heatstroke you should move them to a shaded area and try to cool them down. Call 000 and seek assistance immediately. Radiant heat kills very quickly. The human body cannot absorb large amounts of radiant heat or withstand extremely high temperatures. Radiant heat causes death from heatstroke where the body cooling system fails, leading to heat exhaustion and heart failure.',
                'incorrectResponse': 'Incorrect, but you’re on the right track. If someone is affected by heatstroke you should move them to a shaded area and try to cool them down. Call 000 and seek assistance immediately. Radiant heat kills very quickly. The human body cannot absorb large amounts of radiant heat or withstand extremely high temperatures. Radiant heat causes death from heatstroke where the body cooling system fails, leading to heat exhaustion and heart failure.'
            },
            {
                'q': 'When a bushfire is approaching your property, what should you never do?',
                'options': [
                    'Stay and fight the fire',
                    'Wait and see how close the fire gets',
                    'Leave'
                ],
                'correctIndex': 1,
                'correctResponse': 'Correct! Never wait and see. Whichever decision you make, either to stay and defend, or leave early, make it part of your bushfire plan. The longer you wait to leave, the greater the risk to your life.',
                'incorrectResponse': 'In the end its up to you whether you stay and defend or leave. But you should never wait and see. Whichever decision you make, incorporate it into your bushfire plan. The longer you wait to leave, the greater the risk to your life.'
            },
            {
                'q': 'Leaving when a bushfire has arrived is extremely dangerous and deadly, but if you have no other option where could you shelter?',
                'options': [
                    'A dam or river',
                    'In a water tank'
                ],
                'correctIndex': 0,
                'correctResponse': 'Correct! It is recommended you seek shelter in a well-prepared home that can be actively defended, from a private bunker that is built to regulation, or at a community shelter or refuge. Radiant heat can be blocked by a solid object such as a concrete wall or building which creates a barrier between you and the fire. If you have no other option you can go to your local place of last resort, a ploughed paddock or the beach, dam or river, but dont shelter in water tanks.',
                'incorrectResponse': 'Incorrect. It is recommended you seek shelter in a well-prepared home that can be actively defended, from a private bunker that is built to regulation, or at a community shelter or refuge. Radiant heat can be blocked by a solid object such as a concrete wall or building which creates a barrier between you and the fire. If you have no other option you can go to your local place of last resort, a ploughed paddock or the beach, dam or river, but dont shelter in water tanks.'
            }

            ,
            {
                'q': 'If you know someone in an area affected by bushfires but have been unable to get in contact with them, who should you call?',
                'options': [
                    'The closest hospital',
                    'The local council or shire',
                    'The Red Cross',
                    'Local police'
                ],
                'correctIndex': 2,
                'correctResponse': 'Correct!.The National Registration and Inquiry System is coordinated by the Australian Red Cross. If you are worried about the location of friends or family, call them on 1800 727 077 rather than contacting local agencies. If you are in a bushfire-affected area, when you are able you should call your family and friends to let them know you are safe.',
                'incorrectResponse': 'Incorrect. The National Registration and Inquiry System is coordinated by the Australian Red Cross. If you are worried about the location of friends or family, call them on 1800 727 077 rather than contacting local agencies.If you are in a bushfire-affected area, when you are able you should call your family and friends to let them know you are safe.'
            },
            {
                'q': 'Driving during a bushfire is very dangerous and is a last resort. If you get caught on the road, what can you do?',
                'options': [
                    'Drive as fast as you can through the flames',
                    'Wind up windows, close vents, put on your hazard lights and headlights'

                ],
                'correctIndex': 1,
                'correctResponse': 'Correct! If this is not possible, then pull over to the side of the road into a clear area, well away from debris that may ignite. You should also Wind up your car windows, close the vents, put on your hazard lights and headlights, leave the engine running and air conditioning on recirculate. Get down as low as possible below window level and cover up with a woollen blanket until the fire front passes.If you have water, drink it. Get out of the car only once the fire has passed.',
                'incorrectResponse': 'Incorrect! Cars are a very dangerous place to be during a bushfire as they offer very little protection from radiant heat. Driving will take longer than you expect and road conditions can become dangerous. There may be road closures, smoke, fallen trees and embers.'
            }
        ]
    });
</script>

